- **Pokémon Card Gradient Background Rule**
  - All Pokémon cards (in grids, listings, or details) must use a Tailwind gradient background based on the Pokémon's types:
    - If the Pokémon has two types, use `bg-gradient-to-br from-type1 to-type2` (where `type1` and `type2` are the Pokémon's types, e.g., `from-type-water to-type-dark`).
    - If the Pokémon has only one type, use `bg-gradient-to-br from-type1 to-type1` (e.g., `from-type-fire to-type-fire`).
  - The type color classes must match those defined in Tailwind config (e.g., `type-water`, `type-dark`).
  - **Example:**
    ```jsx
    const type1 = p.types[0];
    const type2 = p.types[1] || p.types[0];
    <div className={`bg-gradient-to-br from-type-${type1} to-type-${type2} ...`}>...</div>
    ```
  - This ensures all Pokémon cards have a visually consistent, type-based gradient background.

- **Applies to:**
  - All Pokémon card, grid, and detail components
  - Any new feature or section that displays Pokémon cards

- **Rationale:**
  - Type-based gradients improve visual clarity and thematic consistency
  - Dual-type Pokémon are visually distinct from single-type Pokémon

